<div>
	<h3>Verb Conjugations</h3>

<p>3 types of verbs. U Verbs, Ru-Verbs, Irregular Verbs (only 2!)
<br>
All verbs end in a U sound, no exceptions: taberu (eat), nomu (drink), iku (go), suru (do)
<br>
</p>
<p>
<h3>Exceptions</h3>
<br>
As in many languages, the extremely common verbs morph over time and become irregular
<br>
In Japanese, the verbs for doing and coming are irregular. You just have to learn the conjugations for them. The nice thing is that they are so common you'll get lots of practice (link to article on each).
<br>
</p>
<h3>Ru Verh3s</h3>
<p>
<br>
These are verbs that end in eru and iru. It's a bit of a strange name - words like wakaru (understand) are NOT RU verbs.
<br>
Examples: eat (taberu), break (kowareru), remember (oboeru), be able to do (dekiru)
<br>
These are super easy to conjugate. Sometimes they are known as one-step verbs because there is only one step to conjugate them. Most of the time, you just drop the final 'ru'
<br>
There are a few U verbs that LOOK like RU verbs (ie. they end in iru or eru) but these aren't EXCEPTIONS as much as sneaky U verbs. to go home (kaeru) etc
</p>
<h3>U Verbs</h3>
<p>
These are known as 5-step verbs because each of the 5 rows of the hiragana chart are used. But only in the column it is. (This is why you need to understand how hiragana is laid out (<a href="" title="">here</a>, even if you can't read it yet).  
<br>
For example: Take the verb, to go (iku)
<pre>
	A ika -nai - don't go
	I iki-masu - mase/formal stem
	U iku (plain form of the verb. Start here)
	E ike-ru - can/able to go
	O iko-u - let's go!
</pre>
</p>

<div>
	<a href="" title="Play the verb conjugation game!">Play the verb conjugation game!</a>
